-- France Stocks Advance; BNP Paribas, Societe Generale, Total Lead the Gains
-- David Altaner
-- 2010-07-02T10:31:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-02/accor-argan-bnp-beneteau-edenred-gdf-jcdecaux-french-equity-preview.html

          
          
             France’s benchmark CAC 40 Index rose
9.7, or 0.3 percent, to 3,349.6 at 12:19 p.m. in Paris. The SBF
120 Index gained 0.3 percent.  
 The following were among the most active stocks traded in
France today.  
 Beneteau SA  (BEN FP): The world’s biggest sailboat maker
gained 3.6 percent to 11.09 euros. Beneteau yesterday said
third-quarter revenue rose to 316.7 million euros ($397 million)
from 272.3 million euros a year earlier and confirmed its full-
year operating profit forecast.  
 BNP Paribas  (BNP FP): France’s biggest bank by assets
increased 1.4 percent to 44.11 euros. BNP and BPCE SA agreed to
form a partnership to share information-technology investments
and costs at their consumer credit units in France. Also, Apax
Partners LLP agreed to buy the company’s Belgian credit-card
unit for an undisclosed sum, according to L’Echo.  
 Edenred  (EDEN FP): Shares in the services unit of  Accor SA 
(AC FP) started trading in Paris today and were trading at 14.24
euros, from a reference price of 11.40 euros.  
 Sanofi-Aventis SA  (SAN FP) France’s biggest drugmaker fell
2.1 percent to 47.23 euros. Sanofi’s CGT labor union
representatives called for a strike July 5 and 6 to protest
planned job cuts. Also, the U.S. House of Representatives
approved a measure limiting the ability of pharmaceutical
companies to make agreements that regulators say keep generic
drugs off the market.  
